[[File:Arabic script-2.svg|thumb|150px|Bannai, [[Isfahan]] 15th/16th century, [[Koran]]-[[Sura]] 112 ''al-Iḫlāṣ''<ref>{{citation/core |Surname1=Ḥabībollāh Fażāʾelī |Authorlink1= |EditorSurname1= |Periodical= |Title=Aṭlas-e Ḫaṭṭ : Taḥqīq dar Ḫuṭūṭ-e Islāmī |Edition= |Volume= |Issue= |Publisher= |PublicationPlace=Isfahan |Year=1971–2 |At=pp.&nbsp;166 |IncludedWorkTitle= |ISBN= |ISSN= |Date= 1971–2 |TransItalic= |language=fa |Other= |ARXIV= |DOI= |URL= |AccessDate= |Comment= <!----> }}</ref> ]] '''Bannai''' is a script form of the Islamic [[calligraphy]]. It was used primarily in [[Iran]] in the building [[inscription]]s. It is a kind of angular [[Kufic]] script, which has [[geometric]] forms like [[square]], [[rhombus]], [[rectangular]], [[Parallel (geometry)|parallel]] and [[cross]]ed [[Line (geometry)|line]]s. The foundation of Bannai script is the [[Horizontal and vertical|horizontal]] and [[Horizontal and vertical|vertical]] directions of the lines, which have always equal thickness and fill completely the geometrical form.<ref> {{citation/core |Surname1=Adolf Grohmann |Authorlink1= |EditorSurname1= |Periodical= |Title=Arabische Paläographie |Edition= |Volume=2: Das Schriftwesen, die Lapidarschrift |Issue= |Publisher=Böhlau |PublicationPlace=Graz |Year=1971 |At= |IncludedWorkTitle= |ISBN= |ISSN= |Date= 1971 |TransItalic= |language=German |Other= |ARXIV= |DOI= |URL= |AccessDate= |Comment=Tafel XXIX <!----> }}</ref>
